{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_parsifal_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608658/1957112301/0625.xml":{"full_text":"A-6\nTHE EVENING STAR, Washington, D. C.\nHATt'RPAT, NOVVMBtX M, ISB7\nssssssyuL\u25a0\u25a0 i\u25a0\njjaHMafe-- *'j SI\nHk\nKVb,\nSUNDAY CLASS FOUNDER\u2014Dr. Eugene\nRice, who helped found one of the Nation\u2019s\nfirst adult Sunday schbols in the Calvary\nBaptist Church 66 years ago, gazes at a pic\nture of the group\u2019s first instructor, the late\nF. W. Vaughn.\u2014Star Staff Photo.\nVaughn Bible Class\nStill Draws Pioneer\nTomorrow, Dr. Eugene C. Rice, 90, will take the wheel of\nhis car to repeat a Sunday journey he has made almost without\nInterruption since 1889, to attend the Vaughn Bible Class he\nhelped found at the Calvary Baptist Church. Eighth and H\nstreets N.W.\nThe members of the adult Sunday school for men recently\nhonored Dr. Rice, who is the\nlast survivor among: the five\nyoung: men who helped the late\nF. W. Vaughn organize the\nclass 66 years ago. It was one\nof the first Sunday schools for\nadults in the Nation.\nWe decided it would be bet\nter if adults went to Sunday\nschool too, right along with\nthe children.\" Dr. Rice ob\nserved. \u201cI have noticed that the\nchildren tend to remain in the\nchurch-going habit if the par\nents retain an active interest.\u201d\nIt\u2019s an 11-drive mile drive to\nthe chutch from Dr. Rice\u2019s\nhorde at 903 Patton drive, Sil\nver Spring. And he drives it\nhimself. He has been a widow\ner since 1948.\nGratitude for Recovery\nAnother old-timer, Francis\nBrown, who joined the class in\n1890. recalls that Mr. Vaughn\nfounded the class with Dr. Rice\nand the others in gratitude for\nhis recovery from a Civil War\nwound.\n\"He was hit at Cold Harbor\nand promised the Lord that,\nif he was spared, he would pay\nHim back,\u201d Mr. Brown related.\nThe class first met in the'\nchurch sanctuary, provided by.\nthe pastor, the late Rev. Sam\nuel Harrison Green. Member\nship multiplied and at one time\ntotaled more than 300 men.\nThe number still exceeds 150.\nOver the years the class\nroutine hasn\u2019t varied. After the\nprayers, the instructor, always\na layman, begins the Bible les\nson prepared by the Northern\nand Southern Baptist Conven-,\ntions. Interpretation and dis\ncussion are part of the class\nhour. Dr. Rice says he has\nnever lost interest in the week\nly meetings, despite his more\nthan six decades of attendance.\nLearns Through Life\n\"They provided me with a\nlifetime of learning,\u201d he says.\nThe short, wiry man. who\nCOMMUNITY CHURCH\nPark Road Community Church\nim\u00bb Park Rd.. N.W.\nTHR REV JOHN T. KHIMAN\nMinister\n30 s m \u2014Church School\n11 am\u2014Morning Worship\n\u00bb.30 p m \u2014Evening Worship\nTuesday. 8 pm\u2014Prayer Meeting\nCHRISTIAN SCIENCE CHURCHES\nCHRISTIAN SCIENCE CHURCHES\nAND READING ROOMS IN\nGREATER WASHINGTON\nBranches of The Mother Church The First Church of\nChrist, Scientist, in Boston, Massachusetts\nSubject of Lesson-Sermon, November 24\nSOUL AND BODY\nGolden Text: P-alim- 86:4. Tlrjnirr llie soul of thy servant;\nfor unto the*. O Lord, do I lift up my soul.\nCHURCHES\nWashington, D. C. Virginia\nFIRST CHURCH FIRST CHURCH\u2014Alexandria\nColumbio Rd. Euclid St. N.W. 1709 RusseM Rood\nSECOND CHURCH 6843 Ljn)e Fo s Rd u\n3160 Pennsylvonio Av\u00ab. S.E. SECOND CHURCH\u2014Arlington\nTHIRD CHURCH 3101 Arlington Blvd. at\n13th and L Sts. N.W, N. Highlond St.\nFOURTH CHURCH SOClETY\u2014Fairfax Town Holl\n3505 16th St. N.W.\nFIFTH CHURCH Maryland\n1238 31 it St N W FIRST CHURCH\u2014Chevy Chase\n1 Zoo 3 st at. N.W, 7901 Conn. Ave.\nSl alai C w UR A H X, C FIRST CHURCH\u2014Hyattsville\n4441 Wis. Ave. NW, Sun. 1 43rd Ave.\n5301 W.s. Ave. N.W,, Wed. F|RST CHURCH\u2014SiIver Spring\nSEVENTH CHURCH Georgia Ave. ond Highland\n1302 Rhode Island Ave. N W. Drive\nHOURS OF SERVICE\nSunday Morning Services and Sunday School ot 11; First Church,\nChevy Chase, First Church, Alexandria and First Church Arlington.\nServices and Sundov School also ot 9:30. Second Church Arlington\nSunday School ot 9:30 and 11. Sunday Jvenmg Services in First\ncm<J Fifth Churchc' Washington ot 8: Third ond Fourth Churches\nWashington at 5. Wednesday evening meetings ot 8 include Testi\nmonies of Healing. First Church Arlington, Foirtax Society ond First\nChurch, Hyattsville, at 8:15.\nREADING ROOMS\nWashington, D C Virginia\n'532 Connecticut Avenue NW. I 10 N. St. Asaph St.. Alexandria\n3160 Pennsylvonio Ave SE. 03C r\n14th 6 G Sts N.W iColo. Bldg I 6835 Llt,le Fol,s Rd Arlln 9ton\n1405 Pork Rood NW. 31 50 Wilson Blvd Rm. 200, Art.\n(Riggs Bonk Bldg. I\n2315 Wisconsin Avenue N.W. Maryland\n4626 Wisconsin Avenue N.W r r-L c-u\n1302 Rhode Islond Avenue N.W. Co n Ave Chcvy Chase\n>6Ol Eye Street N.W 6221 43rd Avenue, Hyattsville\n(Christian Science Bldg. I 8616 Georgia Ave Silver Spring\nAlt Are Cordially Invited to lltend the Services, nnrf to I'isit\nthe Reading Rooms\nRodio Programs: Sun., WARL, 8:45 o.m\nFri., WRC., 6 am. Television Programs Sun, WRC-TV 9:30 am.\n1 looks a good deal younger than\n90. was honored in a special\n1 class ceremony last Sunday.\nHe celebrated his birthday yes\nterday.\nDr. Rice retired 13 years ago\nfrom podiatry practice. He had\nbeen active in the field since\nhe was graduated from George\nWashington University Medical\nSchool in 1897. A son, E. Clar\nence Rice, is director of the\nlaboratories at Garfield and\nChildren\u2019s Hospitals.\nDean to Talk\nAt Cathedral\nThe Very Rev. Francis B.\nSayre, Jr., Dean of the Wash\nington Cathedral, will deliver\nthe sermon during the 11 a.m.\nservice tomorrow in the Ca\nthedral.\nThe Evensong service at 4\np.m. will be all musical. The j\nCathedral Choir of Men and\nBoys, under the direction of\nPaul Callaway, will present the\nprograqj.\nHoly communion will be\ncelebrated by the Rev. Canon\nLuther D. Miller at 9 a.m. in\nSt. Mary\u2019s Chapel and by the\nRev. Canon Theodore O. Wedel\nat 9:30 a.m. in Bethlehem\nChapel.\nOklahoma will be remem\nbered in Cathedral prayers to\nmorrow and the State flag will\nbe carried in the ecclesiastical\nprocessions.\nDIVINE TRUTH\nFRUIT OF\nGRATITUDE\nSubject at the\nCosmos Club Auditorium\n2170 Florido Avc. N.W.\n(Corner of Mass. Ave.)\nUse the Florida Ave. Entrance\nSundoy, Nov. 24, 11 A.M.\nDr. Arthur Jay Green, Minister\nChurch of Divine Truth\nPhone RA. 6-1313\nThanksgiving\nRife Planned\nThe fourth annual national\ncapital service of thanksgiving\nwill be held at 4 p.m. tomorrow\nin First Baptist Church, Six\nteenth and O streets N.W.\nDr. Lawrence Folkemer. pas\ntor of Reformation Lutheran\nChurch, will preach.\nThe service is being sponsored\nby the National Capital Area\nCouncil >of Churches and\nChurch World Service, National\nCouncil of Churches.\nIt will launch a nationwide\nchain of similar observances\nduring Thanksgiving week em\nphasizing the Share-Our-Sur\nplus program of Protestant\nchurches in America. The\nchurehes will appeal for $1 mil\nlion for the 1958 free distribu- j\ntion of nearly S4O million ini\nfoodstuffs to needy people from\nthe Commodity Credit Corpora\ntion stocks.\nAmong those taking part in\nthe service tomorrow are Dr.\nHenry C. Koch, president of the\nNational Capital Area Council\nof Churches; the Rev. Arthur\nF. Elmes, president of the\nWashington Ministerial Union;\nDr. Edward Hughes Pruden,\nminister of First Baptist Church,\nand Dr. Fred'S. Buschmeyer,\nassistant general secretary, Na\ntional Council of Churches.\nWill Talk at Boyds\nThe Rev. E. S. Gault, chap\nlain of the Veterans Hospital,\nBaltimore, will be guest\nspeaker at a homecoming serv\nice at 11 a.m. tomorrow in the\nPresbyterian Church at Boyds.\n'amhl BBfilfe\n\u2019-11 fjp;\nfgp\u00a3|\nS m\nW m Hr\nm Wv\ni\nSL j* n\nWORK LEADER Mrs.\nBarnet R. Brickner, of\nCleveland, Ohio, a mem\nber of the national board\nof the American Associa\ntion for Jewish Education,\nwill lead a Chanukah\nworkshop of the Sister\nhood of Temple Sinai at\n12:30 p.m. Monday in the\ntemple\u2019s new building,\n3100 Military road N.W.\nShe is the mother of Rabbi\nBalfour Brickner, of\nTemple Sinai, and her\nhusband is rabbi of Fair\nmont Temple, Cleveland.\n\u2014Charles Photo.\nUNITED CHURCH OF CHRIST\nI CONGREGATIONAL 5\ns I 10th AND G STREETS N.W. I R\nT I Ministers: Carl Heath Kept C\nDelbert L. AchuH, Jr. H\nMinister Maslr: Whltlord L. Ball Oreanlst: Helm I. Troutman\nM:4ft a m -Church School for All Age*\n11:00 am.\u2014\"CHRIST'S SECOND BLESSING.\u201d Dr. Kopf\n(Nursery and II a m 1\nrt:ls c m\u2014Youth Groups\nIrtbraba (Hongrrgattmial\nNorth Bethesda Junior High School \u2014Johnson Ave. and Ewing Dr.\nGROVER C. RIEGER. Minister\n11 :00 o.m.\u2014Worship Service, Church School, Nursery\nCLEVELAND PARK CONGREGATIONAL\n34th St. N.W. at Lowell Alfred Wesley Hurst. D.D., Minister\n9:15 a.m.\u2014 Family Service and Church School\nI 1 :00 a m\u2014Morning Worship\n\"THE LOST ART OF BLUSHING\"\n7 :00 p.m.\u2014Young Adult Group\nGRACE REFORMED The Nationol Reformed Churtlt\nREV ROBERT W OLEWILER. Paster\nN. REID PRICE. Minister at Music\n9:00 a m.\u2014Worship With Sermon By The Pastor\nII :00 o.m.\u2014Thank Offering\u2014Sermon by Dr. James A. Moyer\n9:45 a m -\u2014Church School (Nursery During .SerticeJ\n3 p m.\u2014Japanese Christian Fellowship in Theodore Roosevelt Room\nANNUAL THANKSGIVING DAY SERVICE THURSDAY, 10:00 A M.\nA (Cmtnirbta\nI' (Four blocks from the White House>\n\"The Friendly Church on the Corner\"\njfag\u00df\u00df* HENRY D. KOCH. D.D., Minister\nA DONALD STUMPF, Student Minister\nM 9 :45 o m.\u2014Bible School\n1 I .00 a m.\u2014Morning Worship\n\"BEYOND THAT DAY\"\ni rtv i irsrrv unrtno Church Service\nThursday, 10:30 o.m.\u2014COMMUNITY\nTHANKSGIVING SERVICE\nWESTMORELAND CONGREGATIONAL\nWestern and Massachusetts Avenues at tha Circle\nPhilip Gordon Scott. P D. Minister\nChriitino Skalton, Director Religious Education Harold Ash, Diructor of Music\n9:30 and 11:00 a m.\u2014Morning Worship. Identical Thanksgiving\nFamily Services\n9:30 and 11 :00 a.m.\u2014No Church School except for Toddlers\nand Nursery\nm \u2014Youth Fellowships\nBP Ah| C'C 4704 13th Street N.W.\nr CvrLE 3 Arthur fletcher elmes. Minister\n9:30 ond 1 I .00 a.m\u2014Church School Sessions\n11 am\u2014Morning Worship: \"A FAITHFUL STEWARD\"\nThursday, I 1 :00 o.m. \u2014Union Thanksgiving Service ot\nPlymouth Congregational Church\n\u201cThe Friendliest Church In The City\nPLYMOUTH 17th and P Streets N.W.\n9:30 o.m\u2014Church School\nHOME COMING SERVICE\nI 1 :0:0 a.m\u2014Morning Worship\u2014Sermon;\n\"THE CHURCH NICE OR NECESSARY?\"\nJamese Clark Brown, Church ot the Epithony, Guest Speoker\nThursday, 11 :00 o m,\u2014UNION THANKSGIVING SERVICE\nLtttrnln fHrmortal (Hmuu-rgattonal armplr\nEleventh end R Streets N.W.\nC. SHELBY ROOKS. Minister\nHrntt Brants Shrsurd. i hoirmuato Oartr Walden Ortanlat\nI I :00 a m.\u2014\"CALLED TO BE WITNESSES/' Dr. Fred Bushmeyer,\nAssociate General Secretary\nWashington Office, Notionol Council of Churches\n9:30 a.m.\u2014Church School\nROCK SPRING CHURCH >nd II m -Wor.hm Srrvlr.\nIIV IHUNUTON -in and 11 a m \u2014Church School\nRock Spring end Little Fells Rd North Mr* Orrald Stryker A.soemu\nI SIDNEY LOVETT. Minister In Reltsloua Education\nFairfax County MV hu c T 7 j S B CKW\n11:01' iw Wor\u00dfhio R#rvic* H\u00abM a 7 Annan*lalf fllrm*nt*rj School\nChurch School for All A*c\u00ab- -Nuraery Carr for Infant*\nm k a\nm 4\\ l X m\ni wtr wW* W\nPi'\nDr. fNINh Dr. Llelea Mrs. Smith Dr. Lchcr\nArea Churches to Hear\nSermons by Visitors\nGuest speakers will occupy the pulpits of a number of\nWashington area churches tomorrow.\nDr. Charles B. Foelsch, former pastor of the Luther Place\nMemorial Church here, will return to his old pulpit for the 11\na.m. service in the church, Fourteenth and N streets N.W. Dr.\nFoelsch Is now president of the Pacific Lutheran Theological\nSeminary in Berkeley, Calif.\nDr. R. T. L. Liston, president\nof King College. Bristol. Tenn.,\na Presbyterian school, will\nspeak at 9:30 and 11 a.m. serv\nices in the Fairlington Presby\nterian Church, 3846 King street,\nAlexandria. He also will ad-:\n'dress the Central Presbyterian;\nChurch. Sixteenth and Irving\nstreets N.W., at 8 p.m.\nChurch Woman\nRuth Juram Smith, of Selins\ngrove. Pa., a member of the\nGeneral Board of the United\nLutheran Church Women and\nwife of the president of Susque-\nhanna University, will speak at j\n9 and 11 a.m. services at Hope\nEvangelical Lutheran Church,\nGuilford drive and Knox road,\nCollege Park.\nThe Rev. Charles Tudor j\nLeber, general secretary of the'\nBoard of Foreign Missions of\nthe Presbyterian Church,\nU. S. A., will speak at 9:15 and;\n11 a.m. services in the Falls\nChurch Presbyterian Church,\nEast Broad and Fairfax streets,\nFalls Church.\nDr. John E. Briggs, pastor\nemeritus of the Temple Baptist\nChurch here, will speak at an\n11 am. service of the North\nside Baptist Church at 1809\nRhode Island avenue N.E.\nThe Rev. Russell Roberts of\nShiloh Baptist Church. Atlantic\nCity, N. J., will speak at a\n3:30 p.m. service in Shiloh'\nBaptist Church, Ninth and P\nstreets N.W.\nDr. Charles Wesley Lowry,\ndirector of the Foundation fori\nReligious Action in the Social;\nand Civil Order, will speak on'\n\u201cCommunism vs. Christianity\u2019\nat 8 p.m. tomorrow in Sts.\nConstantine and Helen Greek\nOrthodox Church, 4115 Six\nteenth street N.W.\nDr. Henry H. Bagger, presi\ndent of the Lutheran Theologi-\nPRAYER\n=t\nHERE\u2019S TOUR HELP\nDfal-A-Praycr\nME. 8-0708*\nDAILY GRACE\nDial-A-Sermonette\nAD. 4-2266\ncal Seminary In Philadelphia,\nwill speak on \u201cChrist and the\nMan of Faith\u201d at 11 a.m. to\nmorrow in Reformation Lu\ntheran Church, 212 East Cap\nitol street.\nKorean Bishop\nThe Rev. Hyungki Lew, Bishop\nof the Korean Methodist\nChurch, will speak at 8:45 and\n11 a.m. services tomorrow in\nthe McKendree Methodist\nChurch, Twenty-fourth and\nLawrence streets N.E.\nDr. Wei-Kuo Lee, associate\nprofessor of history at George\ntown University, former Chi\njnese delegate to th\u00bbUnited Na\ntions General Assembly and a\nI Methodist Christian, will spdak\nin the Milllan Memorial Meth\nodist Church, Parkland and\nI Granoble drives, Rockville, Md\u201e\nat 9, 10 and 11:15 a.m. services.\nThe Rev. Joseph S. Rigell,\ni director of the McKim Com\nmunity Center, Baltimore, will\nspeak at the 11 a.m. service in\nthe Capitol Hill Presbyterian\nChurch, Fourth street and In\ndependence avenue S.E.\nDr. Henry Neumann, leader\nemeritus of the Brooklyn (N.\nY.) Society for Ethical Culture,\nwill speak of \u201cMan\u2019s Greatest\nGlory\u201d at 11 a.m. before the\nWashington Ethical Society,\n1822 Massachusetts ave nu\n|H.W.\nEPISCOPAL EPISCOPAL\nNORTHWEST\na: i i. m\n(Ealljeiiral\nMassachusetts and iTB Daily Services;\nWisconsin Aves. N.W. 7:30 a.m.. Neon, 4 p.m.\nSunday Before 9/ Stale Day:\nAdvent Oklahoma\nB:ooa.m.\u2014Holy Communion, Si. Mory's Chopel\nThe Rev. Canon Luther D. Miller\n9:300.m.\u2014H01y Communion, Bethlehem Chapel\nj The Rev. Canon Theodore O. Wedel\n11 :00 o.m.\u2014Morning Prayer and Sermon\nThe Rev. Francis B. Sayre, Jr.\ni 4:00 p.m.\u2014Evensong\u2014Service of Music\nThe Washington Cathedral Choir of Men and Boys\nExhibition \"Religion and Man in Contemporary Art,\"\nDaily 9 a.m.-4:30 p.m.\nSrrulur Guided Tours Dully trum u.m. ta'\u00ab:SO urn mad Sunday\nfolluwlmr tha II u.ua and 4 o.m. Services\nALL SOULS MEMORIAL\n2300 Cathedral Ave. N.W. (Just East of Conn. Ave.)\nRev. Frank Blackwell, Rector\nH8:30 a.m. \u2014Holy Communion\n9:30-11:00 a.m.*\n\"A CLUB OR A CAUSE,\" Rector\n\"THE RECOVERY OF IDEALISM\"\nOld St. John\u2019s Church GEORGETOWN^PARISH\nWILLIAM SHARP, Rector\nWESTERVELT ROMAINE. Organist\n8 :00 o.m.\u2014Holy Communion\n9:15 a.m.\u2014Family Service and Church School\nI I :00 a.m.\u2014Morning Prayer ond Sermon\nNursery and Kindergarten at live\n5150 Macomb Street N.W.\nvl. uamil 5 bet MncArthut blvd and Loughboro Rd\nTHE REV ALBERT E.